animal.description:
* For a faster response please apply online prior to requesting a meet and greet. Apply at www.6dogrees.com

Meet JMo a male 8-month  deerhed tan and white 6-pound Chihuahua. JMo is seeking a home experienced with little Chihuahua's. Due to his size and skinny legs he must always be handle with care. His energy is very active, a secured fenced area is a must and supervision at all times. JMo must never be left outdoors alone unattended. He also must be kept from  jumping on and off furniture. His long legs are fragile. No big dogsor kids under 17 are to be in his future. JMo seeks a home with dogs his size under 7 pounds. 
  Adoption fee is $625. 

JMo is a fun silly puppy with lots of puppy energy.  He is a sweet boy and you cannot help but smile in his presence. JMo gets along with dogs, and lives to be your shadow. He is a snuggler – he loves people. 
JMo was saved from a high-kill shelter in California.  Due to his small size and tiny stature, he will need to be adopted into a home without children and we are seeking a loving family that is familiar with this breed to provide him with unconditional love throughout his lifetime. 

JMo is a rescue dog, and rescue dogs require routine and stability. Please be prepared for a lifelong commitment before applying.  Ideally, they should be pottied every 4 to 5 hours. Dogs cannot be left alone for 8 hours per day. Home check and plan must be carefully thought out and presented at time of interview. Adopter agrees to purchasing Pet insurance at time of adoption no exceptions.

Jmo is fostered north of Seattle, and if interested please submit an online adoption application at www.6dogrees.com. An adoption application must be filled out for all inquiries and prior to a meet and greet. We will review and respond to applications, not all applications will necessarily be approved for a meet and greet. Home check prior to adoption approval. 

The tax deductible adoption fee of $650.00 is not negotiable. The fee is needed in order for us to "save it forward" for the next dog. The fee covers spay/neuter, microchip, vaccines, deworming, rabies vaccine. We seek the best "fit" home for our dogs.

6dogrees Rescue is a small passionate Seattle based 501c3 non-profit charitable organization that focuses on saving the lives of urgent dogs on their last hours at high kill shelters  from the State of California where pet overpopulation is at epidemic levels and kill shelters are the norm. 100% of all fees collected are spent on the dogs, we “Save it forward”; so each time a dog is adopted we are allowed to save another. Adoption fees are non-negotiable and are in place to allow thorough care for the dogs. 
6dogrees adoptions are limited to residents of Washington State.

**Please read Jackson's entire profile, which includes a link to the adoption application. Thank you!** 

Meet Jackson, a 1-year old, 50-pound. Labrador/Terrier mix young fellow who loves kids.

Jackson was given to his first owner as a puppy, a gift she had not asked for and didn’t particularly want. She kept him outside in small pen that wasn’t kept clean.  Her family give him little to no attention even though he was a sweet little guy.

A rescue agency approached the family and asked them to surrender Jackson so that we could find him the loving home he deserves.  

Now is foster care Jackson loves to play with his human companions and with the other dogs in the home.  Finally getting some attention gets him very excited and he does tend to jump, but his foster family is working with him to help him overcome this behavior and trust that there’s plenty of love to go around. 

It's just sometimes he cannot contain how happy he is to be where people actually care about him.  He’s ready and waiting to show you he’s the very dog you’ve been waiting for.

All dogs are up to date on vaccinations and spayed/neutered at the time of adoption.  All dogs require professional training to become the best family member they can be.

To adopt or learn more about Jackson, you must fill out an adoption application. To find the application, copy and paste this URL into your browser: WWW.GDRNE.COM/ADOPTION-APPLICATION [Adoption Fee: $495]  **  PLEASE READ: If a dog is listed, then s/he is currently available for adoption. Their information is correct to the best of our abilities and the information we have been given as of the day of posting. Please note, GDRNE does not guarantee the breed of any dog or puppy unless stated that we have run DNA. All breeds listed are educated estimates. Our dogs are rescued from various situations. It is most likely that both their parents were strays and even if not, mixes of some sort and that their grandparents were mixes as well. The dog may have some genetic material of an American Staffordshire Terrier (pit bull). The dogs are usually mixes of many breeds, making them a breed all their own - a True and adorable American MUTT. If you are interested in this dog, you must submit an application. Great Dog is not a shelter so there is no building you can visit. Our dogs live in private foster homes until adopted. To learn more about our *shelterless* rescue, adoption fees, and procedures, review the list of Frequently Asked Questions on our website at WWW.GDRNE.COM.

Bella-Abeleza has had a rough go of things and can’t seem to find a home that is just the right fit for her.  Fuzzy Pawz knows that special someone is out there!

Bella loves her adult people and wants to please but NO kids under 15 please.  Bella does not tolerate kids’ noise and chaos; she wants a nice quiet retirement home.

Bella might be a bit older but she still has lots of energy for long walks; doing well on leash.  She does not dig, chew on things she shouldn’t and she’s house trained.  While she likes to go outside her favorite thing is to take a long nap on the couch under a cozy blanket – the perfect reading and tv watching companion!

Easy going is a good description of Bella; she allows her ears to be checked (and they have to be looked at often), sits to get her teeth brushed and will lie down for you to use a Dremel on her nails!!! 

All of that being said Bella does not do well with other animals.  She is fine with some dogs but it is touch and go on who she wants to be friends with.  Honestly Bella would do best in a home with no other pets; she would really prefer not to share her people.

animal.description:
Layla is so good to her caregiver.  She is 5 yrs old and about 50 lbs in size. She has a typical heeler nature which includes being a good protector and worker. Heelers like having a job and Layla is loyal to her family to not only love but, guard them against strange things or people.

We know a bit about her background and she has lived both inside and out. She is housebroken and lived in different family situations in her past. We are looking for a home where she can get daily exercise off leash. Being totally an inside dog tends to make her over protective of her family and she doesn't take well to strangers or strange dogs approaching.  She can show aggression. She is  generally not good with other dogs although she and her sister get along.  No cats for her. 

We feel she is ideally suited to a home outside a city where traffic and unfamilar folks are not a common occurrence. As you can see by her photos she has a kind heart. We are very fond of her and her sister, Laci!  They were raised together and Laci has the same personality and tendancies.

Her fee is $100.

She is fully vetted and recently treated for heartworms. This will require heartguard protection monthly which is not expensive. 

We are a rural shelter with high intakes.  As a result, the shelter dogs are not guaranteed safety. We do our best but, we need help.
ADOPTION FEES APPLY-  Dogs $85-$125.  Cats $60-$80.  (We are not set up for credit or debit payments.)

Please visit or make an inquiry by calling this number 606-663-4998.  Leave a message on voicemail if you miss the staff.  Your calls are VERY IMPORTANT to us!
The shelter is open Monday thru Friday from 9 - 3 p.m. except Thursdays (closed).  Saturday hours are by appt.  

After hours appts can be arranged with advance notice and an approved application.  We want to accommodate! 

For an alternate phone, call 859-948-0371.  We are glad to answer any questions.   Adoption rates are low and include a spay or neuter and rabies. Surgeries are mandatory!

animal.description:
Shadow: 6-year-old black & tan male, neutered, docked tail and natural ears. 15", 28lb. Fully vetted. Rescued from shelter.

"Hi everyone, my name is Shadow! 

Due to unforeseen circumstances, I was removed by Animal Services from my previous home as they were unable to care for me properly. Once the shelter evaluated me and I received all the necessary shots, a nice lady from IMPS came in and rescued me.  That was a great day! I was so glad to be out of that shelter.

I am told I am a little on the fluffy side and my new foster mom is helping me trim down.  I have two brothers and a sister in my new foster home, and I am learning how to play with them. I love playing tug of war with my foster sister. At night my foster parents take turns throwing the ball for me and it’s a race to see which one of us can get to it first.  It’s pretty entertaining, my foster mom had to put down additional area rugs in the living room so I would stop sliding across the hardwood floors like I was Tom Cruise in the movie Risky Business. 

At night I currently sleep in a crate like my foster siblings. When my foster parents go to bed, I like to give a few howls telling them good night and then I settle in. If my new forever family wanted or let me share a bed with them, oh my that would be wonderful.  

I am a mellow, easy going, sweet, friendly, and upbeat boy who loves meeting new people. I also like to chase birds and pretty much anything I think I can catch, therefore I would do best in a home without cats. My foster mom has a doggy door, and I can just run out and do my business whenever I need to, which is pretty convenient. I really like sitting next to my foster mom and cuddling on the couch.  I love getting and giving affection and would be a great companion to my forever family. 

I am hoping that IMPS and my foster mom can find me my forever family who will commit to always taking good care of me and provide me with a proper diet and daily walks.  I see other dogs going and getting homes like that and I really, really want one too. Are you the home for me? I am patiently waiting for you to complete an Adoption Application and meet me.  That way I can meet you sooner. I can hardly wait! I’m excited just thinking about it! 

Here is the Application Link: http://www.minpinrescue.org/home.html

Licks and tail wags,
Shadow"

Note: Shadow is located in Contra Costa County, California  and we will not fly this boy.

If you wish to adopt, please fill out our IMPS Min Pin Adoption Application
If you have previously submitted an Application form, there is no need to re-apply.

For more details about Shadow, please contact Kim: Kimdollensimps@gmail.com

IMPS is a non-profit rescue organization that does not have a viewing facility to which you can come and meet the dogs available for adoption. All of our Min Pins are in loving homes in foster care. Arrangements can be made with the foster parent; however, it is a requirement that the Adoption Application be completed and approved first.

If you wish to adopt, please fill out the IMPS MinPin Adoption Application go to:  http://www.minpinrescue.org/home.html 

Also, please visit our website by going to: http://www.minpinrescue.org

animal.description:
Aria ... if only we knew why you feel so threatened by everything and everyone around you.  

This little munchkin is just over 1 year old [13 august 2019] and naughty as can be.  She is determined and stubborn and wants everything to happen on her terms.  

She is a must for an experienced dog owner only.  Hard no on kids under 15 in or visiting the home.  No other pets in the home.  

She also needs a quiet home, without a lot of coming and going of people.

Once Aria knows you are her person, she becomes a really loving and sweet dog, but she still will not tolerate anything she deems not acceptable, and uses her teeth to let you know.  

Again, a dog that you must be willing to work with a professional trainer to overcome her bad behaviour.

She is young and we know with the proper guidance she really can become a great dog, but she does need quite a bit of assistance getting there.

We have not seen any guarding issues while in foster care, but that's not to say they won't creep back up in a new home.  

Her shelter medial record also notes she has a luxating patella, but we're not seeing signs of lameness with her, so if it or they do exist, they aren't bothering her in the least, which isn't unheard of.

She has had urine testing completed, and it is noted that her urine is slightly concentrated, so she does need to drink more water, so will likely be a dog that needs to be on wet food for life.

Ready to take on this fiesta sweetie? She's still such a young dog, that she can be a better version of her current self with dedication to her training.


FROM HER FOSTER PARENTS:

Aria is a bundle of love. Aria loves her people more than anything. She wants to be with them at all times and always wants to be a part of whatever is going on. She is an expert cuddler and her favourite activity is cuddling in bed. However, Aria is also very protective of her people so she barks at and bites people and dogs that come into the home or that she walks by on her walks.  

Aria also doesn't like physical manipulations. She will bite if picked up or when her harness is being put on or if there is a sudden movement in front of her. 

Aria loves walking and playing. She is almost fully house trained but she still needs to be taken out every few hours to ensure she doesn't go inside by accident. 

Aria does not have separation anxiety. 

Aria has some trouble remembering to eat and drink. Therefore, she needs reminders sometimes to eat her food and she likes it when her people sit with her while she eats. 

Aria does well in the car but will bark at people outside when the car is parked.


FROM THE SENDING SHELTER:

Owner surrender: behavior issues, bite, pees on bed (owner wasn't going outside with her or just sometimes for 15 min max)
Never seen a vet with owner
Barks in her kennel, seems to be protective
wasn't comfortable with the pound employee at first, tries to snap. Tested with a woman (stranger), Aria sniffs and ignores her but once the woman tries to follow her, she started to bark and snap. Owner said she was doing that for attention
Sniffs and cries in new environment, very anxious
OK with physical manipulations if she comes to you. Otherwise she could snap
Possession of her food
No interest in treats, takes slowly but drop them after
Not good with cats
Not good with dogs
Doesn't play at the moment
Could snap with sudden movement
Snaps if you grab her
Doesn't know any command
Pulls a little bit on leash
Not recommended with kids
High energy level
Possession of toys and bones as per owner
Doing her business outside at the pound

____________________________________________

As of today, though our protocols could change tomorrow, we are still moving forward with adoptions. Our process has changed from some of the previous elements: We are a registered animal welfare organization, so we are deemed an essential service.

All paperwork completed online, video home visits, meet and greets outside respecting social distancing, leashes/collars/supplies wiped down and disinfected (GermiCide 3 wipes), disinfectant on the dog prior to handoff (Aqueos wipes for dogs)

-----------------------

To note: the above description is relevant to this dog in his current setting. Home changes & adopter personalities can bring out different behaviours not previously seen.

We do not specifically kid/cat test our dogs when they arrive at Mattie's Place. That just wouldn't be fair to the dog or child/cat.

We also do not claim, endorse, suggest or hint at, that any of our dogs are hypoallergenic, low shed or no-shed.

Adoption fee includes: spay/neuter, deworming, defleaing, vaccinations, nose to tail health exam, leash|collar, 6 months of preventative based on season/need, DNA test for entertainment purposes, dishes, poop bags, food and any extras she has accumulated in foster care.

Update 01/29/2021. Goliath had a dental cleaning today. He did not have any teeth pulled as both teeth and gums are in good shape.

Hi everybody my name is Goliath. But I am not a giant like my names indicates, I am a tiny little 5-6 pound Chihuahua. The dog docs think I am about 5-6 years old but my foster mom says I play like a 2-year-old. I was a stray dog, wandering the streets when I was rescued. The streets are no place for a little dog like me. I am happy to be in a nice foster home with other small dogs. I love playing with the other foster dogs. I am a timid little guy who needs a bit of time to warm up to new people. But once I know you I am a very sweet dog who loves attention.

I am house-trained and puppy pad trained. I sleep in a dog bed at night and I have indoor manners. I love to play outside in the yard. I run around and explore. I must always be supervised when outdoors as I am small and easy prey for other animals. No dog doors for me!.

I am looking for my new forever home. Ideally my forever home will have another little dog to be my buddy. I really need folks to be patient with me as I am scared of new people and need time to warm up. It would be best for me to be in an adult only home or one with older children. I am an easy going guy who is obedient and loyal. If you have room in your home (I really take up no space at all!) and heart please consider adopting me.

Goliath's adoption fee of $350 includes the dental cleaning, vaccinations, microchip and neuter.
If interested in learning more about Goliath, please complete our online application at
https://www.helpadogsmile.org/adopt/application/
. As the rescue does home visits and stays in close contact with the adopter during the adoption transition, only Phoenix area homes will be considered for Goliath.

At SDHS:Blu has been microchipped, neutered, and is up to date on vaccinations. Now he's ready for his new home! Why this pet is the one for you:Meet Blu! He is a high-energy, active guy looking for a loving home to call his own! He gets really excited when meeting new people and doesn't always greet them the polite way. His new home should be prepared to continue his positive reinforcement training. Because of this, his trainers think he would do best in an adult-only home or one with older teens (16+). With having so much energy, he will make a great running or hiking buddy! Blu has a history of finding things to get into when he isn't appropriately mental and physically tired. We think he would be awesome at an escape room, but might decide to practice this behavior in the home. In addition to lots of exercise, Blu should have regular mental enrichment, like Kongs or puzzle feeders to keep him busy. Our Behavior and Training team is looking forward to speaking with you prior to adoption to go over tips for behavior management in the home. And because cats are fun for him to chase, he will need a feline-free home. He would also do best as the one-and-only canine with lots of focused attention. Are you looking for someone to bring some excitement into your life? Blu might just be the one! Click on "Adopt Me" to get started! To be considered for adopting a dog from Canine Lifeline, you must have an approved application must be on file. Please visit http://www.caninelifeline.org/adoption-process/ for more information about our adoption process and to submit an online application.

This handsome 2 year-old guy is Benji. He came to us from an overcrowded rural county dog shelter but we don't know if he was an owner surrender or a stray. All we know that is he came into the shelter with another male dog. Benji, or Big Ben as we like to call him, looks like a mix of Cattle Dog and perhaps Great Pyrenees although that's just our best guess. He made the trip to Canine Lifeline so he could take his time finding the perfect new home. Ben can be a little shy when meeting new people but once he makes friends with someone, he is all puppy--super-silly and very affectionate. Ben seems to love other dogs so we do want to place him in a home where he'll have a confident canine buddy to show him the ropes and boost his confidence. Given his shyness, Ben will also need a home in a quiet neighborhood with a yard that has a secure aboveground fence to keep him safe. For a big guy, Ben walks quite nicely on a leash and is sure to get even better with daily walks in his new neighborhood. We look forward to seeing this boy really relax and start living his best life in his new home. Benji weighs about 61 pounds and his adoption fee is $325. He's neutered, heartworm negative and on monthly preventative, up to date on vaccinations including bivalent canine influenza, wormed, on flea and tick preventative, and microchipped. As part of the adoption process, all adopters must commit to a two-week adjustment period to make sure it's a great match before the adoption is finalized. Please email info@caninelifeline.org if you're interested in Benji. An approved application is required before we schedule meets with any of our dogs. Please note that we don't place our dogs in homes with children under 7 years of age. We correspond via email so please check your junkmail or spam folder to make sure our reply hasn't landed in there. Please visit our website at www.caninelifeline.org to see more photos of Benji and to submit an online application if you live in Northeast OH.

animal.description:
***************************************

Tripper is a soulful 3 year old, 35lb Terrier mix who was owned by a homeless man in Louisiana.  He realized he wasn't able to properly cared for her, and signed her over to rescue.  Her foster mom says, "Tripper has lived in our home since August.  I really can not believe that she has fit in so well.  We have a small Zoo at my house because we have our own dogs (2) but I also foster cats/kittens for a local Humane Society.  I currently have 7 foster cats and we have 5 cats of our own.  A lot of cats to learn to tolerate!  But she does it with ease.  Since Tripper was owned by a homeless person I really did not know what to expect as far as temperament, daily routine, etc., but Tripper jumped right in and just became a part of our family.  She loves our dogs.  She is extremely playful with our younger dog.  She will chase a ball , and can run like the wind.  I would occasionally take them to the river and let them get in the water.  She was afraid at first but eventually would swim around with the other dogs.  Tripper will bark at new people who come to our house but once she is introduced she appears to become more comfortable with them.  I am not sure if it was her job while homeless to let her owner know  someone was approaching.  She is a great security alarm.  She has let me know of deliveries to our house way before I realized someone was at the door.  Tripper has never had an accident in the house.  There are a couple of times when I heard her whine and she was at the door wanting outside.  We are semi retired and my husband makes his rounds to an old warehouse we have,  back and forth to home and a small business we own.  The dogs are with him everyday making his rounds or at the house in the backyard with me.  So they get a lot of exercise running and playing inside the warehouse, and in the backyard of our home.  Tripper knows her name and most of the time if I am taking her with me, I do not leash her from the house to my car because she knows the drill and goes straight to the car.  I have leashed at the collar and she likes to pull, when I have taken her on a walk by herself, I have used a harness and she does well with that.  We do have 2 Grandchildren that stay with us occasionally and once Tripper was introduced she was comfortable with them.  I do not crate her at all.  She is very good about sleeping in her bed all night and actually seems to like her own space.  Our dogs sleep in the kitchen area, and she seems to be comfortable doing the same.  I never tried letting her sleep in the bed, because she always seemed to like her own bed from the beginning.  I would imagine Tripper would make a great family pet, but I also think she would make a great companion for a single person/couple.  She seems to be very loyal and super super smart.  When she first came to our house, she would sit, lay and stay on command.   She is a very active dog and loves to go, go, go and did I tell you she can run like the wind (she is fast).  She does very well in the car and I can see her going on camping trips, taking long walks, or hikes and loving it. One thing I have noticed is that while Tripper and I have a great relationship, she does get very excited when she gets to go with my husband in the mornings.  I am not sure if it is because her previous owner was a male but going with my husband makes her very happy.  I am truly going to miss this girl and her golden ember eyes, when she finds her forever home and transports.  She is so deserving of a happy life and happy ending!"  Please email us at TheChiSociety@gmail.com to apply for this shiny beauty!


Tripper's photo album:  https://photos.app.goo.gl/FaAz1fF9UY1B4zmj6

Tripper videos: 
https://youtu.be/OjobRivbeDI
https://youtu.be/s9DMdfZpKeM
https://youtu.be/m_8125Uzz8M

Tripper is spayed, microchipped, current on vaccinations, and current on monthly heartworm/flea/tick prevention.  Upon rescue, she did test positive for heartworm, but has completed treatment and is now heartworm free.  Yay!

Charlie is an oldie but a goodie. He is a Lab mix who is estimated to be around 11 years old and weighs 58lbs.  Charlie was found living near a dumpster in rural Northeast Louisiana. He was skin and bones and had heartworm disease. While in his foster home, Charlie flourished! He loves to eat and cuddle. He gained 20 lbs and is looking great. He loves going for walks and rides in the car. He gets along well with other dogs and cats.  He sleeps in a kennel at night but gets run of the house during the day. He has only had a few accidents but that was when he first came to foster and they hadn't learned each other's routines yet. He has early stages of glaucoma so will need to be on eye meds the rest of his life. He doesn't mind the drops especially if he gets a treat afterwards. He is precious and will make the BEST friend for anyone.  He may be an older fella, but he has so much life to live and love to give!  Senior dogs are AWESOME! Please email us at TheChiSociety@gmail.com to apply and let us know about your ability to provide daily eye meds for Charlie when you contact us.

animal.description: Hi there, my name is Zora; that name has a Slavic origin and means "dawn". I came to WCHS as a stray and I am cheerfully looking forward to the dawn of a new day when I find my new forever home. I will thrive as the one and only pet in your home; I simply do not appreciate other dogs or felines and they make me uncomfortable. That also means I would not have any fun at a dog park. Plus, as your singular four-legged family member I will be the happy recipient of all your love and attention; I LOVE people. Speaking of people, my family could include gentle and respectful children of all ages. I do excellent with all sorts of handling and adore cuddles, pats, snuggles and scratches. I am a friendly and energetic girl who will need an active family that can provide sufficient exercise. My ancestors were built for chasing down stray cattle and helping with farm work so I prefer to stay busy. I am also smart and am confident that with your positive and patient training I can learn all sorts of things. Apparently, I have not had the opportunity to learn any cues from people but have heard about things like "sit", "down" or "shake" and that sounds intriguing. Since I have been at the shelter, I have been practicing accepting treats more gently when I am reminded to be "easy". I am a strong and sturdy gal, about 75 pounds, but I am also agile so I would like to try my paw at canine sports, dog parkour or maybe even agility. I am also hoping to challenge my mind so I would love to play nose-work or focus games and enjoy mentally stimulating toys; perhaps I could take my meals in a forging mat. I am excellent with all types of handling and think it would be magnificent for you to shower me with your time and attention. If you are looking for an energetic best buddy, I may be the gal for you; I love to run, jump, tackle and cavort. Stop by to meet me in person and check out my dynamic and sizzling personality for yourself.

animal.description:
*Fostered in Waukon, IA
Baxter & Charlie are a bonded pair. Baxter is a male Morkie. He is 11 yrs old.  Charlie is a male Maltipoo. He turned 11 yrs old last July 4th!??
These boys were greatly loved, however needed to be rehomed due to medical issues in the family and inability to give them the attention they deserve. 
They are very happy, apparently healthy, spunky & social dogs, however we are not looking for a home with younger children. They did well with other dogs at a foster home, however they have been the only pets in the home for 11 years, so it would be best if it stayed that way to avoid any potential jealousy issues. Cats will not work with these boys.
These are lap dogs! They will want to be up on the couch, bed, chairs, whatever. An entertaining little duo!! They were "reported" as potty trained, however they can be expected to mark initially at new places due to excitement and nervousness. Be prepared to reinforce potty training behaviors as they have still occasionally had an accident after some time in foster care. After 2 weeks, this has gotten much better. Charlie is no longer having accidents and Baxter has had very few recently.
All of their vet work is done, including dentals. Baxter had to have 21 teeth extracted. Charlie had no extractions.
They would love a home where they get lots of quality time with their family. They do well on leash. Cannot be trusted at all off leash! A fenced yard would be best. 
If you feel that you can meet the needs of these adorable senior boys, please submit an application at www.heartrescueteam.com
They are required to stay together forever as a very bonded pair. Their total adoption fee is $250. (Senior rate of $125 each)

Well hello there! My name is Stella, and I'm at the Santa Maria Campus. I'm a 5-year-old, female, American Pit Bull Terrier/Terrier mix who would do best in a home with no other large dogs.

I'm one chill, relaxed girl who loves to be around people! I love slow strolls on the beach, movie nights cuddled on the couch together, or even keeping you company while you read a book in the park! Are you working from home right now? I'd be a great new co-worker who is quiet and will love to just lay by your side when your on a Zoom call with your team. 

Ready to adopt or want to hear more about me? The shelter is open by appointment seven days a week! Just email adopt@sbhumanesociety.org to make an appointment today!

When you take your new pet home, he or she will have been spayed/neutered, up to date on vaccinations, provided with a permanent microchip identification and a certificate for a free veterinary exam. Our partners at Purina brand dog and cat food also provide food to get you home. 

Transfer of animals may be available between our Santa Maria and Santa Barbara Campuses. If an animal you would like to meet is at the campus further away from you, just let us know when you email, and we will be in touch with you if a transfer is available. Our adoption fees help support our community programs and the next animal who needs our help!

“Hey, Chevy, are you from Texas?”.  

Everything about this dog is Texas big – from his head, to his neck, to his personality, to his heart.  Two hands spread as far apart as they can go won’t go around Chevy’s neck – maybe he’s training to be a linebacker.  His head is as big as a platter.  

And that huge personality – he trots across the play yard likes he owns the world, and then gently sits next to you and gives a kiss.  Give him a rope toy and he’ll shake, shake, shake, then drop it and come over for a pet.  Super eager to please, he sits in seconds flat for a treat and then takes it so gently!  

Chevy is even well-mannered on a leash.  If he wanted, he could drag you across a field without any effort, but instead he trots along and takes care to wait for you to catch up.   Chevy is a big, strong boy who enjoys attention from his human companions.

animal.description: Hi Ya, my name is Cactus Rose and I am a southern belle from the Lone Star State. I am a high-octane girl with a heart as big as Texas. I could share my home with a dog buddy as long as we are compatible; to ensure we can live in tranquility we will need to meet before I make any commitments. My dog friends need to be medium-large size pups who have a similar play style to mine. I am very tolerant and know how to play bow to indicate I am just having fun but I do play rough and can be a little pushy. I should never go to a dog park to play because I do not like small dogs at all and could be too much for some dogs. Speaking of small furry creatures, I absolutely cannot share a home with any cats; they are way too much fun to chase and torment. My ancestors often had the job of mustering and droving livestock so my breed has unlimited energy, a tendency to nip at heels and an independent spirit. Any children in my family should be 12 years or older so they can help with my training; I am a strong 75-pound gal who needs lots of exercise and structure. I am still working on my manners and get a tad wild with handling because I think it is all a game and can get jumpy and mouthy. I am hoping we can do training exercises together to practice my obedience skills; I could excel at agility or other canine sports. To be happy, healthy and well behaved I need plenty of physical and mental stimulation. I accept treats gently and would love to demonstrate that skill if you ask me to ‘sit' or ‘leave it/drop'. I am alert, friendly and eager to please; I promise to be loyal to you forever. I would make an awesome personal trainer to keep you fit and active. Come on by to meet me in person, and experience my dynamic personality for yourself.
animal.name: Cactus Rose

animal.description:
SISSY 
Rat Terrier mix 
13 years old, 29 lbs 

***********************************
Sissy is a 13 year old Rat Terrier mix who weighs 29lbs, but is on a diet!  :)  Sissy came into rescue when her owner had to move into a nursing home. She was taken to a high kill Louisiana shelter, before being pulled by a local foster based rescue.  While getting routine veterinary care it was discovered she has diabetes. It took some time, but Sissy is now used to eating a diabetic diet and taking insulin injections. She is a grazer so her foster mom had to learn how to set feeding times to get Sissy to eat all of her food so she could get her shots. Sissy's foster mom says, "Sissy is a sassy old lady who is set in her ways and does get snappy especially with other dogs when they get too wild. She would do best in a home with other calm animals (or even as an only dog) and no children. Her new family must also be comfortable administering injections twice a day and taking Sissy in for routine check ups to be sure her insulin dose is correct. Sissy sleeps in a kennel at night. This was a spot of contention at first. She would whine, cry, and howl for hours. This was resolved when she realized she wasn't alone. Her foster mom made sure Sissy could see her foster brother in a kennel close by. I think she would be fine out of a kennel, but because I have so many critters and I know she isn't a fan of them, I figured giving her a safe space at night was best. She stays out during the day and does fine. She likes walks and being outside, but does not care for care rides. Sissy is a lap dog at heart once you get to know her!"  This darling girl was uprooted from the only home she has ever known and deserves to find a new family to care for her for the rest of her day.  Senior dogs are awesome!  Especially special needs seniors!  Please email us at TheChiSociety@gmail.com to apply for this adorable girl and please mention whether you have experience with diabetes maintenance in dogs.
animal.name: Sissy

animal.description:
Bear is a very happy , active 65lb Akita Mix hunk of burning love who loves to run and play with other dogs and is great with his smaller cousins! He does want to chase cats and chickens though, so NOT CATS OR CHICKENS.. He is doing wonderful with his house manners and is crate trained and housebroken. He is 1.5 years old.He can be shy with strangers ( especially men ) as we are sure he came from an abusive situation and his previous male owner dumped him down a side road. He just needs the chance to warm up and then he will be your 65lb lap dog best buddy. He is doing well with his basic obedience, food motivated. His biggest accomplishment has been learning to walk nice on a leash and not drag a human. He is very strong thus we found a no-pull easy walk harness is the perfect solution. He does wonderful in a fully fenced yard, he doesn't try to climb over or dig under. Bear loves children but may do better in a home that doesn't have toddlers because he doesn't realize he is a big dog. He is wonderful at the Vet clinic, to bathe and trim nails . Since Bear is the happiest in the colder weather, snow days are a blast, we feel that TN is not where he needs to reside forever. He does take a bit of extra bribery to get him back inside when the weather is cool. He loves to just lounge in the yard contently and is such a great outdoorsy dog. Colder weather states will be his new BEST FRIEND plae to live! Bear is a big fluffy ball of fun and entertainment and is looking for his forever home. He is currently in Tennessee and can transport up as soon as 1/23. If you are interested please email us at ccrnewengland@gmail.com

ADOPTION FEE REQUIRED. Contact ccrtennessee@gmail.com.

Approximate Weight: 60 lbs

I have been working through some confidence issues as my owner never did any training with me, but the rescue sent me to their amazing trainer and he helped me a lot. He says I am a good boy and I love to snuggle, I just need some patience and structure. I can be good with dogs with slow, proper introductions. Strange dogs make me nervous and my trainer says I can be the "fun police"...I don't like it when dogs get rowdy when they are playing.

While I can definitely live in a home with the right dog, I wouldn't mind being an only child. I am so grateful to be given a second chance at finding my happily ever after, could my storybook end with you?!

animal.description:
Chihuahua
Female, 12 years old, 6 pounds

Margarita is as docile as they come and truly goes with the flow. She is visioned impaired and rickety, but so gentle and sweet. She does well with other dogs and is tolerant. This precious girl needs a loving home and someone to bundle her up and show her lots of love. Her mobility is currently limited but she will find her way around the inside of a home and if given access will find herself outside in a warm spot. Otherwise, she shadows her person. She is not ready for long walks and is unable to traverse a set of stairs but can manage a couple. She is curious though and will smell about and explore until settling close to her person. She rides well in the car and settles quickly if she has a comfortable place. 

Margarita is ready to bond with a person. She is relaxed being picked up and is a little head shy but that is because she wants to see a hand before it pets her. A slow presentation reassures her and she quickly relaxes and accepts love. Her ears are so cute and her tiny body could use some added fat. Thankfully, she is a fan of treats. 

Margarita was picked up as a stray and came to us from Hitchcock Road Animal Services.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Spot is a sweet, energetic girl and she enjoys going to the dog park. She likes to play with toys and with the other resident dogs in her foster home and doesn't bother the cat. Spot seems to have the tendency to guard resources and also has some separation anxiety. Her foster family continues to work on these behaviors with her. Spot always lets us know when something is new or a new person is around as she is very alert and can be protective. She can also be a loud barker when she is alerted or very nervous. She has adjusted to life in her foster home and we rarely hear her barking unless someone new is here that she does not know well. Introductions usually go well with Spot but also need to be done slowly.

Spot is crate trained and views that as her safe space so it would be something she needs to start in her forever home. She needs alot more practice walking on a leash and is likely to do much better adjusting to her new home if there is a fenced in yard for her to run and play in.

Spot likes to be scratched alot and is very food motivated. She sometimes makes a purring, rumbly noise when she is being scratched since she likes it so much.

She will need weeks to adjust to her forever home and will need her new family to be very patient with her during that process. She is a sweet and loving dog but it takes time to build up that trust with her. Spot will need a family that is patient as she learns to trust them when she goes to her forever home.

animal.description:
Alana, affectionately known as "Nubs" to her foster family, is looking for a perfect forever home! Alana is a very beautiful 45 pound hound mix with a short cropped nubbin tail (hence the nickname!) who came to CCR from a shelter in Arkansas. Alana arrived at CCR extremely scared, so we sent her to foster care where she could gain some confidence and learn to trust her new friends. After a week or two of adjustment, Alana is doing great! Her foster dad says, " Alana is a very sweet and affectionate dog. She likes to be in the same room with her people whether they are working in an office, watching TV, or playing with her. She loves playing and chewing toys, and any toys she has should be very, very sturdy. When she is comfortable, Alana is a good learner. She can sit, and she learns routines pretty well. When she gets in trouble (chewing shoes), she understands that she is in trouble and usually settles down. She does well with a routine and having access to her safe spaces and toys and occasional rubs. She has enjoyed encountering the neighbor's dog through the chain link fence." Right now, Alana isn't comfortable going for walks outside of the yard, as the noise of traffic and unknown spaces is still overwhelming to her. She is getting more and more relaxed as the days go by, so we expect that with the patience and support of a forever family, Alana will continue to gain confidence and explore new things! For now, though, Alana needs a home with an attached fenced yard where she can play, go to the bathroom, and get comfortable before graduating to leash walking and other things. Alana would do best in a home that is calm and routine-oriented, as she thrives in consistent, stable spaces. She's looking for an adult household that has lots of love and patience to give her as she continues to expand her horizons. Alana is good with other dogs, and may enjoy the company of a mellow, confident pup to show her the ropes in her new home. Alana is house trained.

If you have the loving, stable house that Alana needs, please submit an application at chicagocaninerescue.org!

animal.description:
Ladies & Gentlemen, were excited to introduce our gorgeous baby girl Andi. She's a 7 year old, Border Terrier/Sealyham Terrier Mix that is 35lbs. Andi lives to be loved and to give love to everyone she meets. If you don't like puppy kisses, then Andi isn't the girl for you- we promise she has no boundaries. She's great with kids, loves other dogs & good with cats. Regardless of her age, Andi is just like a big puppy who loves to have fun in the sun. Her hobbies include movie night cuddles, enjoying her long daily walks, playing with 1 of the 6 kids in her foster home, watching the bunnies, car rides & brand new adventures. Andi is 100% potty trained, 100% crate trained and getting better on a leash (she does tend to pull a little bit. Andi also knows all of her basic commands and is just a lover at the end of the day.

Adoption #Requirements: NO EXCEPTIONS
- Fenced in Yard Required
- No kids under the age of 10 (Andi thinks that she's a lapdog)
- We are making it a requirement that Andi has either children or another dog (MUST BE a LARGE BREED) to bond with in her forever home

Andi is currently up for adoption through Lending A Helping Paw Dog Rescue. Her adoption fee is $350 & will include her distemper, rabies, bordetella, parvo, & lepto vaccines; deworming; microchip; heartworm test; fecal test & being fixed. Andi is currently on both flea & tick, as well as heartworm prevention. We kindly ask that you please wait until then to ask any questions.

***PLEASE READ THIS ENTIRE POST & FOLLOW THE INSTRUCTIONS****
 
With the Covid-19 Pandemic going on we are still doing adoptions, but please remember that we are all volunteers and safety comes first. With our rescue being based in the Metro Detroit area, all prospective adopters must live within the state of Michigan (which means No out of state adoptions). Please remember we are not a shelter and are 100% foster based. Once you submit your application, it may take up to 2 weeks for us to get back to you. So please be patient with us.

Again, we kindly ask that you please read the entire post to answer your questions. If you cannot follow the instructions properly, we will skip your application and move onto the next one. We kindly ask that you save any questions, comments or concerns for the phone interview. We kindly ask the following: No phone calls, No pm's, & No multiple emails- We are all volunteers and promise to get back to you within a timely fashion! 
 
Lending A Helping Paw Dog Rescue; previously known as the PRO-PET-OTIC Foundation, is a 100% Foster-Based Rescue that is ran by all Volunteers. Which means that we are not a shelter & each animal is in an actual home with a foster family. We kindly ask that you put any questions within the email & our team of Volunteers will get back to you. With the overwhelming amount of emails please be patient with our 100% volunteer family and we will get back to you. The application MUST BE filled out, a Vet Check MUST BE completed by our team, as well as a phone interview before we do a 'Meet N Greet.'
 
Vet Checks:
When adopting through our rescue, we 'ALWAYS' do a vet check on each applicant's pets that they have owned over the past 10 years. Please make sure to call your vet to grant them permission to release this information to our rescue. That being said, all of the animals in each applicant's home must be UTD on all of their vaccines (DHLPP & Rabies), an UTD Heartworm Test, & currently on both Flea & Tick, as well as Heartworm Prevention. So please make sure that when you are applying that all of your current animals go to the vet that is listed.
 
How To Apply:
If you're interested in adopting one of our available dogs:
1. Email LendingaHelpingPaw313@gmail.com with the dogs name as the subject when you ask for the adoption application.
2. Once you have completed the application, please print it out, fill it out, scan it, & then email it back to LendingAHelpingPaw313@gmail.com. If you do not have a scanner, please take a picture with your phone and we kindly ask that you sent all attachments into one email.
3. Please make sure to call your vet to grant our organization permission to do a vet check on your current pet.
4. If you are interested in more than one dog, please list your top 3 choices on the completed application.
5. Please be honest & truthful on your application. We always do a vet Check. We always do a home visit. And we always have both the prospective families & dogs best interest at heart!

Thank you in advance for all of your love & support,
The Lending A Helping Paw Dog Rescue Family

animal.description: Grace was dumped at a wildlife management center, but that wasn't the worse thing to have happened to Grace. She had a gunshot wound and all of the bones in her front right paw were shattered. She was picked up by Animal Control and then transported to Furkids so that she could get proper Veterinary care. She is now up and running with no lasting physical trauma. She is a loving girl and understandably with her past has some anxiety. Grace has some issues with other dogs in high energy environments where she has reacted poorly, so we suggest she either be the only animal in the home, or with an owner experienced with dealing with reactive dogs. Grace's estimated birth date is 1/21/2019, she weighs 26 pounds, and her adoption fee is $275. Also, she is not eligible for adoption outside of the Atlanta area. If you live in the Atlanta area and want to know more about Grace, please complete a survey at https://furkids.org/dog-adoptions/application. Puppies require a lot of time and commitment. Please make sure your schedule can accommodate a puppy as it will be a member of your family for the next 10 to 15 years. At this time, meeting our dogs is by appointment only. After submitting a survey, an adoption counselor will contact you to give you more information about the dog you are interested in adopting and to arrange for you to meet the dog. Must be at least 21 years of age to adopt.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Please go directly to BFPA.ORG if you are reading about this dog on another website. The BFPA website will provide more information. All dogs on our website ARE available.

Micky is a very friendly and outgoing 70 lbs, Shepherd/Husky mix. He is a senior estimated to be about 11 years old. If you are looking for a laid back and quiet dog who wants to cuddle, Micky could be a good match. He gets along with other dogs and enjoys socializing at the park. He is possessive with food and toys. Humans can give and take food without issue, but he will try to take food/treats from other dogs so he would probably do best as the only dog in his new home. He has not been around cats but he does love to chase other small animals so I don't think he would get along well with cats. When we go to the dog park he has been petted by some young (7-8 years old) children and he was fine. He stops and allows them to pet him before moving on to something else.

Micky is a quiet dog unless he gets excited and wants another dog to play with him. He is totally housebroken. He can go overnight or 6-8 hours at most during the day between potty breaks.

Micky has a moderate energy level. He can play or go for a walk for about 30 minutes, then he will rest, but is ready to go again two hours later. Micky has good leash manners and enjoys going for walks. He would do best in a family with a fenced yard.

Micky is well behaved in the house so we don't use a crate with him. We leave the crate open for him with a dog pillow inside and he occasionally chooses to sleep there on his own. At night he sleeps on his dog pillow in the living room or he goes into his crate voluntarily. Micky's favorite things to do are playing with his toys and socializing with other dogs at the park. He is very smart and has learned the commands, sit and come.

Micky is very sweet, well behaved and extremely cuddly. He likes when humans play with him and his toys, and especially enjoys playing fetch with tennis balls. He also enjoys sitting on your lap and being pet/cuddled as long as possible. Micky is deserving of a home that will love him for the rest of his years. Is your family that home?

EVERY DOG HAS A STORY: Micky is a handsome senior dog who was rescued from a local shelter. Seniors make a wonderful pet and sadly are often overlooked. Could you consider opening up your home for Micky??

Some of the information contained in this biography includes approximations based on our expertise and is not guaranteed.

Applicants must live no further than one hour from Cary NC as our dogs must be seen by a BFPA veterinarian for all medical care prior to adoptions being finalized. Our foster guardians deliver dogs to their new homes for adoption trials and we do home visits to finalize all adoptions. We therefore require applicants to live within an hours drive of Cary NC.

INTERESTED IN ADOPTING MICKY? If so, please fill out our dog adoption application by copying and pasting this link in a new browser window: https://toolkit.rescuegroups.org/of/f?c=WHMSYCNC

Meet Mac a 2 year old, 60 pound Plott Hound mix young dog. Are you an energetic human looking for a very good companion and/or a companion for your other dogs? Meet Mac, a cute and friendly young dog who loves to go on walks/hikes and play games.

Mac will be timid when he first meets you but super friendly once he get use to his people. Mac has been an instant buddy with our two dogs and with a friends' dog, and has politely greeted other dogs during our walks. He has not been around cats or children yet.

Mac is very smart and is house trained and crate trained. He will go in the crate on command. At night he sleeps in his crate and can go 10 hours without having to go out to the bathroom. Mac has alot of puppy energy. He needs a fenced backyard to run and play. He needs an active human to exercise him and play ball with him, he would prefer a furry buddy to chase and be chased in that fenced backyard. He loves very long walks/hikes with his people and greeting other dogs along the way. A five mile walk daily would make him happy!

If you are looking for a loyal companion who will cuddle with you after an active day and wants nothing more than lots of pets and your love, Mac is your dog.

EVERY DOG HAS A STORY: Mac was found as a stray and taken in by a kind rescuer. She took care of Mac, tried to find his owner and even took him to the vet for proper care. She knew she could not take adopt him so BFPA admitted him and is now looking for his forever home. Could that be yours?

animal.description:
WATSON - 7 years old, 74 pounds, house trained, no cats or small/young children, plays rough with other dogs, may need supervision with other dogs, loves to run, loves chasing and retrieving tennis balls, jumps on you in excitement, very vocal when outside, treat motivated, sits for treats.

WATSON ran and ran outside like he was racing the wind! He is a middle aged boy at 7 years old and what a hoot! He immediately took off when we dropped the leash, found a toy and took full advantage of being outside in that yard at that time. He loves being outdoors and he loves playing. Sound like your kind of dog? Keep reading...Watson was surrendered after starting to show some guarding behaviors when it came to his food and toys. He will give clear warnings, however, so the behavior is manageable if you are willing and able to keep one step ahead of him when it comes to food and toys. He is a fun boy who will keep you on your toes and moving. Watson was pretty vocal I will say when it came to me throwing the ball! He would sit on command and wait about half a New York minute before the barking would start. I'm pretty sure he was yelling, THROW THE BALL!THROW THE BALL! Ha Ha! Watson is a friendly boy who will enjoy and need daily exercise and playtime, and training and attention with the possible guarding behavior. He might be ok with some dogs but we think he will play very rough and with the guarding behavior, well, supervision will be very important. He should be in a home without cats and small children. Call the Virginia Beach Animal Care and Adoption Center at 385-4444 or go to our Facebook page to make an appointment to meet him!

This beautiful girl is Judy! She is a 57 lb, 3 year old, Heeler mix. Judy is the perfect house dog. She is leash, crate and house trained. She doesn't mind cats and can co-exist with dogs but much prefers people. Judy loves snuggling on the couch and belly rubs. She ended up at a shelter in Texas as a stray. Judy was microchipped and had been adopted as a puppy. When her owner was contacted, they said she had been gone for about 3 weeks and they didn't want her back because she kept wandering off. Judy is a sweet girl who is looking for her furever home.

If you are interested in any of our dogs, please complete our online adoption application:

http://www.lifesaverssp.dreamhosters.com/adoption-applicat
/

We will conduct a phone interview, check references and then a home check. This helps us to match a dog with their potential adopter. The adoption fee is $350.00 for adults and $450.00 for puppies under one year which includes spay/neutering, up-to-date age appropriate vaccinations, flea/tick & heartworm preventative and a health certificate. We foster our dogs in homes, not in shelters. This allows us to get to know the dogs temperaments in order to match them to a home. This also allows us to get the dogs ready to live in their forever homes! All dogs coming from the south have been quarantined for two weeks and fully vetted before traveling to New England!

For more info please email Lifesaversapps@outlook.com OR visit our website:

http://www.lifesaverssp.org/

I am available for adoption; however due to my breed my adoption will have to be facilitated through a rescue organization. Please see the front desk staff or contact the Shelter at (248) 858-1070 for more information.

Meet Hattie! Adorable Hattie is looking for a home to call her own! This sweet, sweet girl was found fending for herself, and a very nice family cared for her until they could bring her to the Shelter. While she was in their home, she did very well with their small children and their resident dog. Hattie is a happy girl, who is friends with everyone she meets. She enjoys greeting people, at her kennel, when they come to see her. Hattie deserves to be in a home where her new family will properly care for her and love her for her lifetime!

The following descriptions describe behaviors that were observed during testing and/or veterinary examination: Evaluated for temperament with 336261 and 336498 (males) and 336753 (female). Did well with all, gets wiggly and vocal. 1/19/21

American Pit Bulls are a misunderstood breed; for this reason, we implore adopters to these beautiful dogs to be very vigilant in training and socialization. This breed is very energetic and will need daily exercise. Because of their strength and energy, apartment living may not be the best fit. This breed can be loving, loyal and very smart. 

The above behaviors and personality traits have been observed while at the Shelter. If this animal was relinquished, information is gathered from the owner regarding behavior. Our wonderful volunteers spend time with these animals and give input on behaviors and traits. However, this description may not be all inclusive to how this animal will act in a loving forever home. Introduction to established family pets should be slow and monitored always. The same goes for children and other family members. Adopting a pet is a big decision and should be thoughtful. We suggest researching different breeds to match traits and personalities to your lifestyle. When adopting a pet, please know that this pet will be with you for their lifetime; patience and consistency will make for a successful adoption.

animal.description:
Life hasn't been easy for this guy. Buddy was originally found as a stray and although the finder had good intentions, and tried to care for him, he was unable to provide what was needed. 

When Buddy came to us just before Christmas, he was in rough shape. He had a lot of skin issues, ear infections and was suffering from seizures. With all that going against him, he was still “Mr. Personality” plus!  With the help of medication, his seizures are now under control ?? His ears have cleared up and his skin is about 90% healed. Through all of his medical treatments, Buddy remains a kind soul who loves attention.

Sweet Buddy is a Cur mix, 2 1/2 years old and 70 lbs. He gets along well with other dogs, cats are unknown and because of his size, he needs a 6 ft fenced yard. Buddy has a perfect name because he just wants to be somebody's Buddy.  Give him that opportunity! 

If you want to meet Buddy, please contact us at Adoptions@SuncoastAnimalLeague.Org.

animal.description:
SAY HELLO TO WEEZY! THIS BOY IS FULL OF PERSONALITY! HE IS GREAT WITH OTHER DOGS (HE MAY SEEM BOSY BUT HE ONLY WANTS TO PLAY, PLAY, PLAY!) HE IS JUST A PUP AT HEART. HIS ORGINAL OWNER SURRENDERED HIM BECAUSE WEEZY WAS HER HUSBANDS DOGS AND HE HAD RUN OFF WITH ANOTHER WOMAN. SHE HAD NO USE FOR HIM EVEN THOUGH SHE SAID HE WAS A VERY, VERY GOOD DOG. HE STAYED ON THE FRONT PORCH WHEN HE WASN'T INSIDE. AT HIS FOSTERS HOME HE IS ALLOWED OUTSIDE WITHOUT A LEASH WHEN HIS HUMANS ARE OUT. HE NEVER OFFERS TO WANDER OFF. HE IS A VERY LOYAL FELLA AND JUST WANTS TO LOVE AND BE LOVED. HIS FOSTER FAMILY ADORES HIM AND ONLY WANT THE BEST FOR HIM....A FAMILY TO CALL HIS OWN. HE IS ABOUT 6 YEARS OLD AND WEIGHS ABOUT 65 POUNDS. HE ABSOLUTELY ADORES CHILDREN OF ALL SIZES! HE IS PROTECTIVE BUT NOT IN AN AGGRESSIVE WAY. HE WILL STAND BESIDE OR FOLLOW AROUND ANY CHILD PRESENT. HE IS THE PERFECT NANNY DOG! 
WEEZY IS NEUTERED AND UP TO DATE ON VACCINES. HE IS HEART WORM NEGATIVE AND ON PREVENTION. HE IS ALSO MICROCHIPPED. HE HAS NOT BEEN TESTED WITH CATS. HE IS KENNEL TRAINED AND HOUSE TRAINED. HE EVEN WALKS PRETTY GOOD ON A LEASH.LOCATED IN CROSSVILLE, CUMBERLAND COUNTY, TN. WE CAN TRANSPORT OUT OF STATE

animal.description:
MADDEN....HE'S A BIG, BIG CHUNCK OF PUP! IN HIS PREVIOUS LIFE HE WAS AN OUTSIDE DOG AND HE HAD A FEMALE FRIEND TO HANG OUT WITH. SHE WAS ADOPTED LONG AGO BUT MADDEN WAS HEART WORM POSITIVE & HAS HAD TO WAIT TILL HE COULD BE TREATED. HE WAS TREATED THE END OF OCTOBER 2020. HE HAS NOT BEEN RETESTED AND CAN REMAIN POSITIVE FOR MONTHS AFTER SUCCESSFUL TREATMENT. HE IS NEUTERED AND UP-TO-DATE ON VACCINES. 
MADDEN'S PREVIOUS OWNERS REPORTED THAT HE WAS GOOD WITH OTHER DOGS/CATS AND KIDS. HE HAS NOT BEEN TESTED WITH CHILDREN SINCE COMING INTO RESCUE AND HAS SHOWED SOME FENCE AGGRESSION WITH OTHER DOGS AT HIS FOSTER HOME. FOR THIS REASON HE IS NOT WITH OTHER DOGS AT THIS TIME BUT IT MAY JUST BE THE FENCE ITSELF MAKING HIM BARK AND GROWL AT DOGS THAT GET TO CLOSE TO HIS KENNEL. WE THINK HE MIGHT JUST BE OK WITH A LARGE FEMALE DOG BUT WE SUGGEST A MEET AND GREET BEOFRE ADOPTING. HE HAS SHOWN NO AGGRESSION WITH HUMANS AND IS VERY SWEET. HE LIKE TOYS, ESPECIALLY BALLS. WE'D LIKE TO SEE MADDEN LEARN TO BE AN INSIDE DOG AND WE JUST KNOW HE WILL THRIVE! HE IS ALL ABOUT HIS HUMANS (AS PYRENEES ARE) AND BEING A PART OF THE FAMILY WOULD BE HIS DREAM COME TRUE. HE SPENDS TIME IN AN OUTDOOR KENNEL DURING THE DAYAT HIS FOSTERS HOME BUT HE IS BORED. IN THE EVENING HE IS BROUGHT INSIDE BUT IS PLACED INTO HIS OWN LARGE KENNEL. THIS BIG LOVERBOY NEEDS A HERO THAT LOVES A BIG FLUFFY DOG!LOCATED IN CROSSVILLE, CUMBERLAND COUNTY, TN. WE CAN TRANSPORT OUT OF STATE

animal.description:
Coming Soon for local adoption in Birmingham, 

Calling all sports fans! This handsome black tri is Garth.  Garth is a high energy, high drive, athletic working type that is always on the move.  It is clear that in his former life he did not receive a lick of training, so while in foster care he has been working on appropriate behaviors (he's a jumper), basic obedience commands, and leash training.   He is food and toy motivated, and should do well with an Aussie savvy adopter well versed in positive reinforcement training or with the help of a trainer.  

Garth has loads of potential and his foster mom thinks he would do very well with someone who needs a new agility or flyball partner.
Dog sports not your thing?  That's ok if you are an active human looking for an adventure dog.  Garth will play fetch until your arm falls off, run until his partner collapses, or hike until you run out of daylight.  He is very active and his new adoptive family must be as well.  Garth is no couch potato and will require a lot of exercise and stimulation in order to thrive in his new home.  

Garth would not do well in an apartment situation and needs a physically fenced yard to frolic and play fetch with his new family in order to help burn off some of his endless amounts of energy (I'm serious here, the fetching never ends) He also gets along with cats (although he thinks they all should want to play with him).  He plays well with his foster pack, although he was dog-selective coming out of the shelter, so any canine family members should attend Garth's required meet and greet in Birmingham, Alabama where he is fostered.  

Garth is also a bit unsure meeting new people, until they give him snacks....and then he will be your best friend for life, so his new family should be willing to continue socializing him and building his confidence.  Apologies, but applications with children in the household under the age of 13 will not be considered due to Garth's energy requirements.
Garth is a super fun dog and will do well with an adopter who loves to be active with their dog, or who may want to dabble in dog sports in the future.  He would not be best suited to a first time Aussie owner due to his high drive.
 
Garth is approximately 1.5 years old, 40 pounds, housebroken/crate trained, UTD on vaccines and neutered. He is fostered in Birmingham, Alabama and a meet and greet will be required.

If you think Garth is the guy for you, please fill out our application:

https://www.australianshepherdsfurever.org/adoption-application

All adoption fees are used for future rescue efforts.

animal.description:
Meet Benji! 

Benji is a bonded pair and will only be adopted along with Rosie.

Rosie (9, chi) and Benji (7, pom X) offer you the best of both worlds. Rosie is an outgoing goofball, Benji is the most handsome, more gentle, reserved one. They both get along well with other dogs and cats. They both like short walkies, and Benji loves spending the day at daycare! 
Rosie is well potty trained once you have her timing down. Benji is a little more unsure out in the big world and we are still working on potty training. I think he would do best with a fenced in yard. They can both make it through the full night.
They both love people. Rosie is quick to lay down for all the belly rubs, and Benji will politely pat you to request more scruffs when you stop. They both tend to be pretty quiet (except for Rosie snorting and purring). Benji's previous owner would have him sedated for grooms and kept him in a close body clip.  That's why he has his majestic lion's mane!
These two have been well loved and vetted but medical issues caused their mom to release them to us to find the best new home for them together.

Interested in meeting Benji? 

All Ma, Paws & Me Pet Rescue dogs are in homes with foster families; we do not have a shelter where dogs are available for daily viewing.

Our process is as follows:
1.  Review our policies and adoption radius  on our website: http://mapawsmepetrescue.com/adopt/
2.  Submit an application for review and approval;
3.  MPM Rescue reviews application and checks vet records and references;
4.  MPM foster contacts approved applicant(s) to arrange a home check and meeting with available dog(s);
5.   If there is a good fit, adoption is completed with a contract and fees (payable via check or cash).

The adoption fee is listed here: http://mapawsmepetrescue.com/adopt/

animal.description:
The temperature is dropping in Chicago, and it's time you meet the perfect snugglebug to keep you warm aka Taz! Taz is a beautiful boy with a sweet soul to match and the happiest tail wag. He is estimated to be around 4-6 years old, which means he's grown out of the demanding puppy stage and into adulthood (but still loves a good squeaky toy)! Taz will provide a great balance for his future family - he is quite content to lounge around on the couch curled up by your side, but he also enjoys a brisk walk outdoors to explore the sights and sounds around him. Taz should be the only pet in the home as he has a high prey drive

and also, he likes to sprawl out on the couch leaving just enough room for him and his human(s). He has not been tested with children, but I think he would prefer older kids who can understand and respect boundaries. On walks, Taz is very intrigued by other dogs and sometimes reacts or pulls towards them, but it's easy to manage by just crossing the street when you see one coming and redirecting his attention with a "sit" command and treats. He is a smart dog who will flourish with a loving and confident owner to lead him. We're currently working on crate training to help with barking when his human leaves the house. All in all, Taz is a gem who is potty trained and loves to get 9+ hours of sleep a night!

If you are interested in adopting Taz, please fill out an application at: https://www.dogsaredeservingrescue.com/adoptable-dogs/adoption-application/

animal.description:
Carefree, easy going outlook to life! Our pretty lady in pink Dixie is such a delight. It's hard to not gravitate towards this irresistible two tone bully mix! In laying my eyes on her as another volunteer walked her, I had to scurry over to learn more about her. "It's Dixie. She's a sweetheart." In no time, I too had my special time with Dixie. Dixie does not disappoint and nicely greets all with a soft tail wag and grin on her face. Very attracted to the squeaky toys in our play yard, she happily trotted around with a variety of toys in her mouth and engaged in a moderate game of "play fetch" which quickly segued into "let's go visit the humans" and show them some TLC. Dixie is a smart, affectionate girl who impressed us with her "sit" and then her tongue sticking out as sadly, I had no treat to offer to her but she sat hoping I might have one! This mild mannered lady with the bunny soft fur is a real crowd pleaser and would nicely fit into almost any home environment. Ask for Dixie today and let her bring some winter warmth into your home today!

Our adoption fee includes neutering, microchip, appropriate shots, and a post adoption veterinarian wellness check.

animal.description: This handsome guy is Ernie. He came all the way from a shelter in Kentucky to find his forever home! He was adopted and in a home for about 5 months but was returned due to the owner having allergies. Ernie does not like being in the kennels and he is a little stressed and nervous in that environment. Once he's out he really opens up and he is a happy, silly guy full of personality! We aren't sure what his past was like but based on some of his behavior and condition, he may not have had the best life. He has a large scar on his back that we aren't sure how he got and can be a little nervous and shy when first meeting new people or being in a new situation. Once you gain his trust though, he will be a silly, happy, playful dog. He likes being outside, being goofy, and running around exploring. He loves playing with toys and flipping them around. He loves getting back and butt scratches and being playful. We don't know much about his past so we do recommend he meet any potential "dog siblings" before going home with them. He is an active and strong guy so may be a little too much excited energy for small children. Ernie may also need some basic training skills once in a new home. He has a lot of love to give and just needs someone willing to show him that he is safe and loved and he will be a happy and loyal friend to them. If you think Ernie would be the perfect addition to your family, please call for special adoption considerations, fill out and send in an application so our staff can review it, and if approved, we will contact you about setting up a time to meet him!

animal.description: Hi! My name is Chief and I am a 6 year old Pit Bull Mix, I recently made my way up to Michigan from a very crowded shelter in Arkansas and man is it cold here!! I am a very sweet guy who loves to be around people and cuddle up next to them, I do my best to make it directly on peoples' laps but I have some arthritis so that makes it a bit more difficult. When I first came here they noticed that my hips were stiff so they did some x-rays and it shows that at one point I had some fractures from previous trauma, I can't remember what happened but they tell me that arthritis and pain medications should help me. None of this seems to bother me though, I am a very happy guy who loves to go for walks- I even do a little happy dance when I get to go outside- and I would love to find a quiet home of my own! I have been around other dogs and I seem to enjoy them, but I would prefer a calmer dog that wouldn't play too rough with my arthritis. If you are interested in meeting me please call the shelter to set up an appointment, I hope to meet you soon!- Love, Chief

Gray and white

All Ma, Paws & Me Pet Rescue dogs are in homes with foster families; we do not have a shelter where dogs are available for daily viewing.

Dogs from Ma, Paws & Me Pet Rescue come with the following medical care already provided:

- Microchip
- Deworming
- Heartworm and Flea/Tick Preventative
- Any other necessary medical treatment as recommended by veterinarian

animal.description:
Medical Note: I have an enlarged spleen. My bloodwork is fine, and it is not hurting me.

Hi my name is Miami! I’m 11 years old and 33 lbs! 
Miami is super sweet and loving!  Even though she’s 11, she’s still got some pep in her step...ruffle a chip bag or any food bag and you will see what I mean.  When she’s excited she even has a little bounce.  Her potty manners are pretty good.  If she’s been sleeping for a while and she comes up to you, it means she probably needs to go out.  She does great with my kids (5&8) and her foster brothers.  One is much bigger than her and the other is about the same size.  She loves some good belly rubs, treats, and a soft comfy dog bed.  She is very food motivated and loves her some treats! She knows sit and walks well on a leash. I’ve not crated her, but she sleeps on a dog bed in my room with no issues.  She snores and grunts a little when she gets really active.


You can still come adopt me or even join our foster program to help the humans learn all the awesome things about new dogs like me! Learn more on our website! 

Hope to see you soon! 

What breed am I? Mixed mutt! ODHS does not breed label (unless there’s official paperwork), as studies show it is nearly impossible to tell the exact breed of each dog based off of their appearance.

Educational article:
3/3/3 Rule:
https://www.rescuedogs101.com/bringing-new-dog-home-3-3-3-rule/?fbclid=IwAR2iv5m7fqk3FieO7LOsstGeGsYYV_F1rJOd1BPxaImofLpcinpYsUbFRWs

Adoption Donations are $250 for an adult, $350 for puppies (a dog under one year of age), and $125 for a senior dog (based on the age of the dog). Adoption donations are to be made via cash, and credit/debit card. There is a $5 fee to run cards.

Please remember to bring a collar and leash (non-retractable) with you the day of the adoption. Note: Martingale collars and slip leads are strongly recommended.

Due to COVID19, we aren't having as many open, public adoption events.  Current schedule is pre-determined meet and greet appointments are Wednesday evenings and on Saturdays. 
Our adoption center is located at 3602 Lafayette Blvd, Suite 102, Fredericksburg, VA 22408. It's important that you keep an eye on your emails for any changes or updates during the adoption process.

Visit our website for an application to adopt. 
https://www.olddominionhumanesociety.org/adoption-application

Old Dominion Humane Society is a volunteer based organization. We are run completely by volunteers, who also have full time jobs, so we appreciate your patience.  Currently, the average timeframe for a response to your application is 1 week.

Like us on Facebook "Old Dominion Humane Society"
and be a part of promoting forever homes for dogs in need.
#Adopt #Donate #Foster #Volunteer 

Note: ODHS only adopts to Virginia and surrounding states (including D.C.). A $50 out of state fee applies.

animal.description:
Hey, German Shepherd lovers - meet Bo! This gorgeous boy is about 2.5 years old and weighs 73 lbs. He came to Pet Rescue after his owner died and is adjusting to life after losing the only home he's ever known. He is a very sweet, affectionate and sensitive boy who is friendly and playful with the two dogs in his foster home—in fact, his new home must have another friendly dog to help him feel comfortable and lead the way. Bo is also fine with cats. He is very smart and knows basic commands, is housebroken, very respectful in the home, wants to please and thinks he's a lap dog. He gets nervous around loud noises and would not do well in a city environment. He recently discovered the joy of going to the dog park... he enjoys meeting other dogs and romping around with them, and loves fetching balls. But his most favorite thing in the whole world is to be with his humans. He sleeps contently on a dog bed next to his foster mom at night and would love to find a calm home that will love him and give him time to adjust to all the new sights and surroundings.

 
If you are interested in this dog, please submit an application directly to our website at www.ny-petrescue.org.  Only applications submitted directly to Pet Rescue will be considered.

animal.description:
We have welcomed 13 beautiful puppies to Real Time Rescue and we are looking for WONDERFUL families for each of these puppies! 

We have 8 females and 5 males. Each puppy will be spayed/neutered, have all puppy boosters completed, deworming completed and will be microchipped prior to adoption. The puppies will be available to go into Foster to Adopt approved homes at age 12 weeks old. Each approved home will be required to purchase a crate for their puppy and crate train their puppy, provide puppy food, puppy pads and chew toys. Each approved home should be ready to "puppy proof" the home, work on potty training, be prepared for puppies chewing on things and the occasional whining or crying that comes with owning a puppy.  Once the foster completes a 30 day trial period and everyone feels the puppy is a good fit with the home we will have you complete adoption paperwork. Each puppy is microchipped to our rescue and we will remain the Primary contact on the microchip. Once the adoption is completed, we will add the adopter as a secondary contact to the microchip. Each puppy will grow to be a Large Breed Dog, mom is a pit bull mix and dad was a black shepherd mix. 

If you are ready for a gorgeous puppy now is your chance!
